quran[18]{c,v,t,f}:
44,1,"Ha'. Mim."
44,2,"By the Clear Book."
44,3,"We revealed it on a Blessed Night, for We were intent on warning; {1}",footnotes:1:The meaning of taking an oath by the lucid Scripture has been explained in (E.N.1 of Surah Az-Zukhruf). Here also what has been sworn by is that Muhammad (peace be upon him) is not the author of this Book but We are the author
44,4,"(We revealed it on the Night) wherein every matter is wisely determined {1}",footnotes:1:The word amr-in-hakim as used in the text has two meanings:
44,5,"by Our command. {1} Verily, We were set to send a Messenger",footnotes:1:In Surah Al-Qadr
44,6,"as a Mercy from your Lord. {1} Surely He is All-Hearing, All-Seeing, {2}",footnotes:1:That is
44,7,"the Lord of the heavens and the earth and of all that is between them: if you would only have sure faith. {1}",footnotes:1:The Arabs themselves admitted that Allah alone is the Lord (Master and Provider) of the Universe and of everything in it. Therefore
44,8,"There is no god but He: {1} He gives life and causes death. {2} He is your Lord and the Lord of your forefathers of yore. {3}",footnotes:1:The real God Who alone has the right that He should be worshiped and served.That is
44,9,"(But the fact is, they lack certainty) and frolic about in doubt. {1}",footnotes:1:In this brief sentence an allusion has been made to an important truth. Even atheists or polytheists do come across occasions when their being from within says: There is somewhere some weakness in the creed that we have adopted. The atheist may apparently be very firm in his denial of God
44,10,"So watch for the Day when the sky will come down with a pall of smoke,"
44,11,"enveloping people. That will be a grievous scourge."
44,12,"(People will then say): “Our Lord, remove this scourge from us; we shall believe.”"
44,13,"But how will they take heed? Such are they that a Messenger {1} came to them clearly expounding the Truth,",footnotes:1:Rasul-i-mubin has two meanings:
44,14,"yet they turned away from him and said: “This is a well-tutored madman.” {1}",footnotes:1:What they meant was: this was a simple man
44,15,"Yet We will hold the scourge back for a while, (but no sooner than We will do so) you will revert to your old ways."
44,16,"The Day when We shall seize them with a mighty seizing, that will be the Day on which We shall inflict upon you full retribution. {1}",footnotes:1:The commentators have seriously disputed the meaning of these verses
44,17,"Indeed before that We subjected the Pharaonites to the same test. A noble Messenger {1} came to them",footnotes:1:The words rasul-un karim in the original imply a man who is characterized with most noble traits of character and highly praiseworthy qualities.
44,18,"(and said): {1} “Deliver to me Allah's servants. {2} I am a trustworthy Messenger to you, {3}",footnotes:1:That is
